            <p>Several strategies can help minimize or avoid probate. Holding assets in joint tenancy with right of survivorship allows them to pass automatically to the surviving owner. Naming beneficiaries on retirement accounts and life insurance keeps those assets out of probate entirely. Payable-on-death (POD) and transfer-on-death (TOD) designations on bank and investment accounts work similarly. A revocable living trust can hold other assets outside probate. The right combination depends on your assets, family situation, and goals — which is why we tailor every plan to the individual client rather than offering a one-size-fits-all approach.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
