        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How do I contest a will in Pennsylvania?</h3>
            <p>To contest a will in Pennsylvania, you must file a caveat with the Register of Wills within one year of probate. Common grounds include lack of testamentary capacity (the person did not understand what they were signing), undue influence (someone pressured or manipulated the person into signing), fraud, or improper execution under 20 Pa.C.S. § 2502. Will contests are heard by the Orphans' Court. You must have standing to contest — meaning you would inherit if the will were overturned. These cases are factually and emotionally complex, so early consultation with an attorney is essential.</p>
